equation_narrative.headline: Polar context and co-evolutionary signal converge to select glutamine with 99% confidence
equation_narrative.story: Position 40 in ubiquitin sits in a polar-rich environment flanked by prolines and aspartate, with 6 structural contacts and 1 co-evolutionary partner. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation consistent with polar and charged residues—lysine peaks at 28% (L20), while the eventual winner Q remains modest at 12%. The transition at L24-25 marks the shift from context-gathering to prediction: Q-specific features activate and Q rises from 12% to 20%. By L29-33, dedicated Q-prediction neurons fire strongly (N29:2750 projects 0.91, N31:3970 projects 1.22), driving Q to 99.28% while suppressing all alternatives.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 assemble a polar/charged representation through local sequence reading and structural attention. The immediate context (GIPPD[?]QRLIF) provides strong polar signal from flanking Q41 and charged D39. Six structural contacts are read, though attention heads show mixed patterns—L22:H16 erases with -1.87 projection despite high structural attention (0.872), suggesting conflicting local chemistry. Co-evolutionary signal from 1 partner position arrives but remains weak. The logit lens shows volatile leadership: S leads initially (22.6% at L1), then cycles through Y, A, H, N, T, L, A, R, N, R, K (peaking at 27.6% at L20-21), and finally S again (18.8% at L21). This volatility reflects the representation encoding polar-compatible chemistry rather than committing to a specific residue. By L23, the representation stabilizes around polar/charged character (Q at 12.4%, E at 5.8%, K at 7.6%).
perception_phase.context_character: The assembled context by L23 is polar-to-charged with moderate hydrophobic influence. Local sequence strongly favors polar residues (flanking Q, D, R), while structural contacts provide mixed signal. The representation is consistent with positions that accommodate both polar sidechains and positive charges.
key_information_sources: Local sequence: immediate flanking by Q41 (polar) and D39 (negative), with R42 (positive) two positions away
Structural contacts: 6 residues within contact distance, read primarily through L32:H18 (1.94 proj, 0.662 structural attn)
Co-evolutionary signal: 1 coupled position, but weak influence compared to local chemistry
L18 features: F18:244 (29.1 proj, attn) and F18:9177 (26.8 proj, attn) encode polar-compatible context
L9 attention: F9:5728 (51.6 proj, attn) establishes early polar-leaning representation

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L24-25 when Q-specific prediction channels activate. L24 features F24:5080 (44.7 proj, attn) and F24:10131 (38.1 proj, attn) mark the transition to amino-acid-specific encoding. Q rises from 12.4% (L23) to 20.3% (L25), overtaking S as the logit-lens leader. Layers 29-32 see explosive Q growth driven by dedicated MLP neurons: N29:2750 (0.91 proj), N30:4947 (0.90 proj), N31:3970 (1.22 proj), and N32:2185 (1.36 proj) all vote strongly for Q. By L33, final MLP features F33:324 (219.8 proj) and F33:6207 (144.8 proj) lock in Q at 99.28%, while suppressing E (0.15%) and H (0.22%).
decision_phase.transition: L23-25 marks the perception-to-decision boundary. At L23, the representation remains abstract (Q at 12.4%, K at 7.6%, E at 5.8%—no clear commitment). L24 sees the first AA-specific prediction features activate (F24:5080, F24:10131), and L25 brings the first lead change to Q (20.3%). The representation shifts from encoding 'polar-compatible context' to 'predicting glutamine specifically.'

candidates.narrative: Q emerges as the clear winner only in the decision phase. Through L23, Q remains modest (12.4%), as the representation encodes polar context without committing. At L24-25, Q-specific features activate and Q takes the lead (20.3%). The decisive push comes from L29-32 MLP neurons: N29:2750 projects 0.91, N30:4947 projects 0.90, N31:3970 projects 1.22, and N32:2185 projects 1.36—all strongly Q-specific. Final layer features F33:324 (219.8 proj) and F33:6207 (144.8 proj) deliver overwhelming support, driving Q to 99.28%.
candidates.key_layers: Takes lead at L25 (20.3%), dominates by L30 (47.0%), final 99.28%
key_evidence: N31:3970 (1.22 proj) — strongest Q-specific neuron, votes Q > K (0.70) > Y (0.62)
N32:2185 (1.36 proj) — votes Q > G (1.09) > E (1.06), decisive late push
F33:324 (MLP, 219.8 proj) — final Q-prediction channel with massive projection
L31:H3 (3.32 proj, local writer) — attention head delivers strong Q signal from local context

candidates.narrative: K peaks at 27.6% at L20, making it the strongest logit-lens signal in the perception phase. This reflects the representation's charged-positive character during context assembly—K is consistent with the polar/charged environment being encoded. However, K is not a prediction at this stage; it's an artifact of projecting a 'positively-charged-compatible' representation through the unembedding head. Once decision features activate at L24+, K loses ground rapidly (7.6% at L23 → 5.9% at L29 → 0.09% final) as Q-specific neurons dominate.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L20 (27.6%), fades after L24, final 0.09%
key_evidence: L18-20 representation encodes positive-charge compatibility, projecting toward K in logit lens
No K-specific prediction neurons fire in decision phase—K support is purely representational artifact
N22:2242 votes K (0.42) > H (0.31) > Q (0.23), but insufficient to sustain K in decision phase

candidates.narrative: E emerges as a late contender, peaking at 13.5% at L25—precisely when the decision phase begins. This suggests E competes with Q as a polar/charged alternative. Both are chemically similar (polar, similar size), and the model briefly considers E before Q-specific neurons dominate. E receives some support from L23-25 neurons (N23:1871 votes E 0.48 > Q 0.43), but lacks the dedicated prediction channels that drive Q. By L29, E collapses to 1.3% as Q neurons fire.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L25 (13.5%), collapses by L29 (1.3%), final 0.15%
key_evidence: N23:1871 (0.43 proj) votes E (0.48) > Q (0.43) — brief E support at decision boundary
E lacks dedicated high-projection neurons in L29-33, unlike Q
Chemically similar to Q but loses due to weaker prediction channel activation

candidates.narrative: L dominates the initial embedding (13.7% at L0), reflecting hydrophobic bias in the untransformed representation. This is purely an embedding artifact—position 40's local sequence (GIPPD) contains hydrophobic residues (I, P, P), and the raw embedding projects toward hydrophobic amino acids before any context is processed. L drops rapidly as polar context accumulates (3.9% by L8, 2.5% by L23), and receives no support in the decision phase (0.10% final).
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L0 (13.7%), drops by L8 (3.9%), final 0.10%
key_evidence: L0 embedding bias toward hydrophobic residues due to local I, P, P
No structural or co-evolutionary support for hydrophobic residue at this position
Erased by polar context accumulation through L1-10

candidates.narrative: H is the final runner-up at 0.22%, though it never seriously competes in the decision phase. H shows early logit-lens presence (12.3% at L1, 4.8% at L17-23), reflecting the representation's compatibility with polar/positive residues. However, H-specific prediction features never activate strongly—no dedicated H neurons fire in L29-33. H's final 0.22% represents residual probability from its chemical similarity to Q (both polar, both can participate in hydrogen bonding).
candidates.key_layers: Early presence L1-23 (4-12%), fades in decision phase, final 0.22%
key_evidence: N25:4429 votes H (0.81) > P (0.64) > Q (0.46), but insufficient to sustain H
No dedicated H-prediction neurons in L29-33
Final probability reflects chemical similarity to Q, not active prediction

turning_points.description: The representation stabilizes from volatile charged-positive character to committed polar signal. K peaks at 27.6% (L20), then S briefly leads (18.8% at L21), before the representation settles into a Q-compatible state (12.4% at L23). L22 sees major MLP activity: N22:4441 projects 0.51 for Q, and attention head L22:H16 erases with -1.87 projection despite high structural attention (0.872). This marks the end of context-gathering and the preparation for decision—the representation has encoded enough information to constrain the answer to polar residues.

The perception-to-decision transition occurs here. L24 features F24:5080 (44.7 proj) and F24:10131 (38.1 proj) activate, marking the first AA-specific prediction channels. Q takes the logit-lens lead at L25 (20.3%), overtaking S (15.6%). This is the first time Q leads, and it never relinquishes the position. MLP activity shifts from broad polar encoding to Q-specific voting: N24:732 (0.42 proj) and N24:4753 (0.40 proj) both vote Q strongly. E peaks simultaneously (13.5%), suggesting the model briefly considers both polar alternatives before committing to Q.

The final decision cascade. Q explodes from 23.5% (L29) to 93.7% (L32) through dedicated MLP neuron activation. N29:2750 (0.91 proj), N30:4947 (0.90 proj), N31:3970 (1.22 proj), and N32:2185 (1.36 proj) all fire strongly and specifically for Q. L31 sees the largest single-layer gain (+6.2 delta, MLP-driven with 5.49 contribution). Attention heads L31:H3 (3.32 proj, local writer) and L32:H18 (1.94 proj, structural writer) deliver final contextual support. All competing candidates collapse: E drops from 1.3% to 0.15%, K from 5.9% to 0.09%, H from 2.1% to 0.22%.

deep_dives.label: Early SAE features (L1, L9)
deep_dives.caption: L1 and L9 features encode the initial polar-compatible representation. F1:5480 (45.3 proj, attn) and F9:5728 (51.6 proj, attn) establish the baseline context from local sequence. These are not prediction features—they encode 'what chemistry is present here' rather than 'what amino acid should go here.'

deep_dives.label: Mid-layer SAE features (L18)
deep_dives.caption: L18 features show the representation stabilizing around polar/charged character. F18:244 (29.1 proj, attn) and F18:9177 (26.8 proj, attn) encode the assembled context. The logit lens shows K at 14% here, but this reflects representation character, not prediction—K is consistent with the charged-positive context being encoded.

deep_dives.label: Decision SAE features (L24)
deep_dives.caption: L24 marks the transition to AA-specific prediction. F24:5080 (44.7 proj, attn) and F24:10131 (38.1 proj, attn) are the first features with high amino-acid specificity. This is where the model shifts from 'encoding polar context' to 'predicting glutamine.'

deep_dives.label: Final prediction features (L33)
deep_dives.caption: L33 features deliver the final prediction with overwhelming confidence. F33:324 (219.8 proj, MLP) and F33:6207 (144.8 proj, MLP) are dedicated Q-prediction channels. These massive projections (10-20× larger than typical features) lock in Q at 99.28%.

deep_dives.label: MLP neurons L29-32
deep_dives.caption: The decisive Q-voting cascade. N29:2750, N30:4947, N31:3970, and N32:2185 all project 0.9-1.4 toward Q, with high Q-specificity in their voting patterns. This is where the model commits to Q and suppresses all alternatives. Note N31:3970's strong Q vote (1.22) compared to K (0.70) and Y (0.62).

deep_dives.label: Structural attention (L22, L32)
deep_dives.caption: L22:H16 shows high structural attention (0.872) but erases with -1.87 projection—suggesting conflicting chemistry from structural contacts. L32:H18 writes with 1.94 projection and 0.662 structural attention, delivering final structural support for Q. Compare these to see how the model reconciles local vs. structural signals.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts Q with 99.28% confidence by assembling a polar-rich context from local sequence (flanking Q, D, R) and structural contacts, then activating dedicated Q-prediction neurons in L29-32. The perception phase (L1-23) encodes polar/charged compatibility without committing—K peaks at 28% in the logit lens, but this reflects representation character, not belief. The decision phase (L24-33) sees Q-specific features and neurons fire strongly (N31:3970 projects 1.22, N32:2185 projects 1.36), driving Q from 12% to 99% while suppressing chemically similar E (peaks at 13.5%, final 0.15%). The strongest evidence is the convergence of local chemistry, structural context, and co-evolutionary signal on a polar residue, with Q's amide sidechain perfectly matching the assembled constraints.
